  <div class="comment-content">

    <div class="edit-comment-hide">
      <div class="comment-body markdown-body markdown-format js-comment-body">
          <p><em>From <a href="https://code.google.com/u/101551507304868996625/">Frank.Vi...@googlemail.com</a> on March 06, 2011 10:09:04</em></p>

<p>Hello Ludwig,</p>

<p>At first i wanna say that i'm not involved in map rendering or binary file design...<br>
I think your proposal (a) is critical with regard to performance. The names consume a lot of space since they cannot be compressed efficiently on tile granularity, so this would end up in reading a lot of data (which is not of interrest) during the process of rendering. My guess would be that it suffices to support multiple encodings within the map binary, but at the same time using a separate map file binary for each language. </p>

<p>Another approach would be to decouple the names from the rest of the data,<br>
by moving the names to a separate storage area for each language (names clustered by geographical position), and addressing them inderectly from within the tile data blocks. Don't know if this would do fine, but it shurely means alot of work. (This way the names could also be reused by other components like the routing graph) ... just one option, but i think this is too much contrary to the current architecture and also causes additional flash reads. </p>

<p>The question here seems to be how to trade of flash read costs with the amount of required "disc". </p>

<p>best regards, <br>
frank</p>
      </div>
    </div>

