  <div class="comment-content">

    <div class="edit-comment-hide">
      <div class="comment-body markdown-body markdown-format js-comment-body">
          <p><em>From <a href="https://code.google.com/u/113327232123772191739/">LudwigBr...@gmail.com</a> on March 16, 2011 01:44:57</em></p>

<p>Thank you for your responses and your interest in my proposal. It was certainly meant to kick-start some discussion over this issue and not a fully thought-through concept.</p>

<p>1) Changing map file format: I would not worry too much about it as long as new features are supported and there is no significant overhead for those who do not require the new features. </p>

<p>2) Size of mapfiles: that certainly becomes an issue and maybe one as a whole better solution would be to have separate 'language-pack' files, but this would mean that files can easily go out of sync. Any format for this should of course not create significant overhead if no name is available in a particular language.</p>

<p>3) A much simpler solution, which might provide 80% of the benefit at a fraction of the cost, is what has been suggested in Comment <a href="https://github.com/mapsforge/mapsforge/issues/2" class="issue-link" title="Large areas have incomplete background color">#2</a>: having a parameter in the mapfile-writer, which language to choose from the name tags. With the notoriously inconsistent OSM labelling I would suggest that this would be built as some sort of short-circuit mechanism, eg: 'name:en | name:int | name:xx | name', which would pick the first name tag available, thus ensuring that features will get a name if one is available in the OSM data.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

  </div>
