  <div class="comment-content">

    <div class="edit-comment-hide">
      <div class="comment-body markdown-body markdown-format js-comment-body">
          <p><em>From <a href="https://code.google.com/u/113327232123772191739/">LudwigBr...@gmail.com</a> on May 21, 2011 22:20:34</em></p>

<p>The more I think about this issue, the more I think that actually a solution that would embed multiple languages into the mapfile would be the best solution as only this allows a user to switch languages (or the switch could be enabled via Android localization features, e.g. automatically choosing German translations if the user's language is set to this). This is one area where it is possible to beat Google's maps in quality/user friendliness, so it should not be ignored.</p>

<p>An automated transliterator inside the app is probably not desirable, mainly because of the complexity of the task that IMHO requires adaptations whatever the map region is (a problem of the OSM data, which is so inconsistent in tagging).</p>

<p>The quickest solution is to have a script that performs the necessary changes to the OSM data. I have attached a Python script that does just that, tested with for some Greek areas. It requires only a standard Python installation with the unidecode package installed (get it from Pypi).</p>

<p>The use is as follows:</p>

<p>python transliterator.py greek input.osm output.osm</p>

<p>The script will try to take the greek name from the OSM file (either from name:el or name) and append to it either the int_name or the english name or a transliterated form of the greek name (shortcircuit mechanism). The resulting file can just be processed as before. While the results are not ideal due to OSM data and the length of the resulting name strings, it is a workable solution, and easily adaptable to other language regions or output requirements.</p>

<p><strong>Attachment:</strong> <a href="http://code.google.com/p/mapsforge/issues/detail?id=90#hc5">transliterator.py screen1.png</a></p>
      </div>
    </div>

  </div>
</div>

